<m1>M<m2><ql>
<m0>usic can evoke moods and gleaming pictures in sound. Tone poems by Liszt, Strauss, Tchaikovsky and others have proved that. But because music consists of tones rather than words, it's impossible to know the true meaning of a musical work, <m0>unless<m0> the composer chooses to reveal it. Once that's known, even the most familiar piece sometimes assumes a sharply different character.<ep>
  Take the music of Dimitri Shostakovich.<ep>
  The composer's popular <m0>Festive Overture<m0>, for example, is a rousing curtain-raiser often heard at pops concerts. It is relentlessly jubilant, fast and furious, almost hysterical at times. Its mood of celebration conjures images of dancers whirling about desperately with fixed, forced smiles.<ep>
  But this loud and brash score takes on a whole new meaning when you learn from the composer's memoirs that the exultation you hear is Shostakovich's delirious joy at the death of Stalin. Just learning that makes the <m0>Festive Overture<m0> seem suddenly savagely sardonic, and you can never hear it again in quite the same way (--) certainly not as a holiday pops piece.<ep>
  The Symphony No. 11, subtitled<m0> The Year 1905<m0>, is another<m2><ql>
<ql>
